<div style="font-size:larger"> <b>References, for further reading:</b> </div>

<ul>

  <li> The now-classic textbook <i> <a
  href="http://books.google.com/books?id=mlOa7wPX6OYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=golub+van+loan&source=bl&ots=lbirc1J6l1&sig=KsE7jVOJeHvwRxCDSQRAn-RgdaY&hl=en&ei=Q3bLTMicBYqr8AbX3tG0BQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false">
  Matrix Computations</a></i>, by Golub and van Loan has lots of
  technical detail that our textbook doesn't. </li>

  <li> For plenty more detail on backward errors and condition numbers
  for least squares problems, refer to the very detailed report <a
  href="https://ccse.lbl.gov/Publications/sepp/leastSquares/LBNL-52434.pdf">"Optimal
  Sensitivity Analysis of Linear Least Squares"</a>, by Joseph F. Grcar.
  </li>

  <li> For more on smoothed analysis of Gaussian Elimination, with and
  without pivoting, refer to <a
  href="http://www-math.mit.edu/~spielman/SankarThesis.pdf">"Smoothed
  Analysis of Gaussian Elimination"</a>, the Ph.D. Thesis (MIT, 2004) of
  Arvind Sankar. </li>

  <li> Jonathan Shewchuk's 1994 paper <a
  href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~jrs/jrspapers.html">An Introduction to
  the Conjugate Gradient Method Without the Agonizing Pain</a> is a good
  read, despite the exaggerated negativity of the title.

</ul>

